{{endnote page-numbering}}
Page Numbering in this Ritual Book

This edition of the Cryptic Ritual begins its page numbering at 201. Because all
Cryptic Masons also hold membership in a Chapter of Royal Arch Masons, and
because the ritual of that body is unlikely to exceeded 200 pages in past, current,
or future editions, this allows Companions the option of combining both rituals
into the same binding for conveniene. Additionally, it reduces the potential of
confusion when references are made by number to specific pages in this or any
previous or alternative forms of Cryptic Ritual.

{{endnote costumes}}
Costumes for Degree Conferrals

Other versions of the Cryptic Ritual have included the following instruction:

%SIZE 83%
%COLUMN 0.7in
%SPACE 0.1in
%SPACING 0.2in
If available, the specified dress should be used during degree work:

The Illustrious Master and Deputy Master each wears a royal robe of Purple with a
crown upon his head and scepter in his hand.

The Principal Conductor of the Work wears a robe of orange, with a turban upon his
head and a mallet and trowel in his hands. If the robes of the Chapter are used, the
P._C._W. may wear the Scribe's robe. In the first section of the R._M. degree, he should
wear a plain drab robe and turban.

In the Royal Master Degree, up to twelve robes with flowing sleeves and twelve
turbans may be used, either white, gold or scarlet, for the Cherubim. In the Select
Master Degree, up to sixteen drab robes for the craftsmen. The remaining officers and
active members may wear a robe or gown of purple and a purple turban. The Captain of
the Guard, Steward, and Sentinel, however, may be clothed in ancient military
costume, with a helmet upon the head, and a sword in hand. If the robes of the Chapter
are used, C._G. shall dress as the Captain of the Host, C._C. shall dress as the Master of
the Third Veil, and the Steward as the Principal Sojourner.
%SIZE OFF
%COLUMN OFF
%SPACE 0.1in
%SPACING 0.3in
This is a good basic specification for costumes, but should not preclude the
possibility of other simpler or even more elaborate wardrobe decisions that may
not exactly match these details. Work together as a Council to make costuming
decisions. Do a full dress-rehearsal, and honestly ask yourselves, "Do these
costumes contribute to the solemnity and serious nature of our rite?" Poorly
maintained or outdated costumes may detract from the experience, having
opposite of their intended effect. In such cases, the attire worn for your Stated
Assemblies may be preferred.

{{endnote securing-doors}}
Securing the Doors

Other versions of the Cryptic Ritual authorized by various Grand Councils have
omitted an instruction to Secure the Doors, potentially leading to a situation where
the Companions are asked to be in order (and to give the sign(s) of the degree)
while prying eyes could, in theory, be looking on. This would obviously be an
error, and any well-governed Council has always informally secured the doors
before beginning their ceremonies, but this has now been formalized and brought
into harmony with the rituals of the Symbolic Lodge and of the Royal Arch
Chapter which are in use in our Masonic Jurisdiction.

