{{endnote ancient-usual}}
... an Ancient Number, and a Usual Number.

The Ancient Number (2 for the R._M. and 27 for the S._M. degree) holds symbolic
signifiance, as explained in the ritual, while the Usual Number allows for the
officers to be listed and called up for recitation of their duties. The Usual Number
is given as "Nine or more, although [[underline]]six[[/underline]] are sufficient for business," which allows
all subsequently named officers, if present, to be called up, while also stating the
minimum number to constitute a Quorum for the purpose of a business meeting.
This minimum number is sometimes known as the "constitutional number," as it
must reflect the number required to constitute a Quorum as expressed in the
constitutions and By-Laws of the Grand Council.

[[em]]See also End Note for Page {{bookmark-page endnote-twenty-two}} on "Twenty-two from Gebal, Ahishar, Adoniram,
and our Three Grand Masters..."[[/em]]

