{{endnote psalm-87}}
Psalm 87 at Opening

A variety of options may be entertained here, including silence, a simple reading
of the Psalm, instrumental music or a lyrical rendition of the Psalm (either pre- |
recorded or performed.)

If opting for a musical rendition, it is not essential to include the entire text of
Psalm 87, neither to adhere to any particular translation, nor to the verse and line
divisions represented in the Ritual. Existing musical arrangements may use the
wording "many excellent things" in lieu of "glorious things," for instance.

The appropriateness of this Psalm to our Order is found in its listing of several
nations and tribes that were historically adversarial to Israel, such as Rahab |
(Egypt), Philistia, and Babylon. They are here treated as being metaphorically <|
born in Zion by the phrase "this and that man was born in her," describing a |
harmony which should prevail based upon a recognition of the universal
brotherhood of man, which was anciently prefigured in the coming together of
those who built Solomon's Temple, and especially those who worked upon the
Secret Vault. This same symbolic expression is also present within the parts of the
Cover or Key Word which Royal Arch Tradition informs us was deposited upon
the Substitute Ark.

{{endnote high-twelve}}
"High twelve."

Although the hours for work on the Select Master Degree are defined as "nine
at night `til low tweve, the time when prying eyes are closed in sleep," the time for
Refreshment is still paradoxically given as "High twelve." This is not a mistake,
and the General Grand Council's Ritual also includes "announce high twelve, and
proclaim the time for refreshment and labor" among the P._C._W.'s duties, while
opening on the Select Master Degree.

