{{endnote rm-divine-pronouns}}
Capitalization of Divine Pronouns

%SPACING 0.22in
In the 19th century it became a common (although, not universal) practice to
employ a form of "Reverential Capitalization" for pronouns when they are used in
reference to the God of the Abrahamic religions. Whereas the earlier King James
Version of the Bible renders Psalm 33:21 as "For our heart shall rejoice in him,
because we have trusted in his holy name." Young's Literal Translation of 1862
renders the same verse with capitalized pronouns as "For in Him doth our heart
rejoice, For in His holy name we have trusted."

In modern times, this practice has become less common, and it is recommended
against by various style manuals including [[em]]The Christian Writer's Manual of Style[[/em]],
[[em]]The Chicago Manual of Style[[/em]], and [[em]]the Associated Press Stylebook[[/em]], while other
style guides such as the 2008 [[em]]US Government Printing Office Style Manual[[/em]]
actively prescribe it.

In this work, the capitalization of pronouns has not been employed unless at the
beginning of a sentence. This decisions is made for two primary reasons:

%INDENT -0.15in
[[strong]]Consistency:[[/strong]] Because our Masonic work includes frequent quotations from the
King James Version of the Bible, it was deemed more reasonable to avoid
changing the text of the Biblical quotations.

[[strong]]To Avoid Theological Decisions:[[/strong]] Because some of the decisions regarding
exactly which pronouns would have been capitalized and which would not
rested upon precise sectarian theological interpretations, this determination
falls outside of the boundary of Masonry's Compasses as "the handmaiden of
religion."  The decision not to capitalize these pronouns allows each Mason to
read or hear the words of our ritual in the way most applicable to his own
religious understanding.
%INDENT 0

While pronouns are not capitalized, we have nonetheless attempted to capitalize
the various proper names and titles directly used for Deity, such as God, the
[[smallcaps]]Lord[[/smallcaps]] or Supreme Grand Master, in addition to many terms of Masonic
significance which (although not divine names,) are capitalized to draw attention
to their specific Masonic meaning. In this category fall the various Working Tools
such as the Square and Compasses, officer's titles such as Companion Captain of
the Guard, and formal terms such as the Master Mason Degree.
%SPACING 0.24in
%PAGE
{{endnote rm-candidate-names-see}}
Pronouncing Names of Candidates

See End Note for Page {{bookmark-page endnote-candidate-names}} on this same topic.

{{endnote reverential-posture}}
Reverential Posture of Cherubim

The most important aspect of this reverential posture is that the Cherubim in the
Degree Team have an agreement or understanding in advance about which posture
will be used, based upon number present and their attire. The following advice
should serve as guidance in arriving at that decision:

%INDENT 0.15in
[[strong]]If there are enough Cherubim[[/strong]] available to form a circle about the altar, having
"wings outstretched" so that the tip of the wing of one touches the tip of the wing
of the next, allowing for enough space inside to circumambulate the altar, then that
is the preferable arrangement.

[[strong]]If there are less Cherubim,[[/strong]] they should be stationed giving priority to those on
the north and south of the Altar, then to the West side of the altar, forming a
symmetrical arrangement. With fewer Cherubim, rather than touching wing-to- |
wing, it may be more sensible for each to face inward and make a prayer gesture
individually. [[strong]]If costumes include flowing sleeves or draped wings[[/strong]] attached at
the hands or wrists, a classic or stereotypical posture of prayer may be most
effective: Each Cherubim should press the fingertips of their left and right hands
together a few inches in front of their mouths, and bow their head. [[strong]]Otherwise,[[/strong]]
the group may elect to use the Position of Reverence described on Page {{bookmark-page attention}}.

The question may also arise as to whether the Cherubim should kneel. While it
is true that the Cherubim described upon the Mercy Seat covering the Ark of the
Covenant have been often described in a kneeling posture, yet of those larger
Cherubim which in the description of Solomon's Temple are said to have reached
from wall to wall, we have no indicator as to whether they knelt, or stood upon
four or two legs.

[[strong]]If all Cherubim are capable of kneeling,[[/strong]] kneeling may be utilized here to
good effect if agreed upon by the Degree Team in advance.
%INDENT 0

{{endnote hirams-prayer}}
Hiram's Prayer

Other versions of the Royal Master Degree have offered a selection of various
prayers to be recited by Hiram Abiff. To promote a more uniform quality of
experience for those receiving the degree, the prayer in this edition incorporates
excerpts from those prayers while being more particularly composed with the
intent to further the symbolic teaching of the Degree.

