%PAGE
{{endnote significant-gesture}}
The Significant Gesture

The Lecture of this degree will refer back to H._A.'s significant gesture depicted at
this point in the ceremony. This gesture consists of three raps on the ground, the
pointing of his finger at the Altar, and the words which are spoken at the same
time.

Rather than merely stamping the foot three times, it may be worthwhile for H._A.
to stamp his foot in a forward motion, towards the altar, or even to carry a rod or
walking-staff with him, and rap the end of it on the ground in a gesture forward
towards the altar.

This gesture suggests multiple layers of meaning, all of which may be seen in
relation to the Ancient Master's [[smallcaps]]Word[[/smallcaps]], now known as the Grand Omnific Royal
Arch Word or I._N._O._D. It points to the location of the Secret Vault (beneath the
Sanctum Sanctorum), to the altar of obligation (by which we promised to keep it
secret), to the symbolic place of H._A.'s prayer (by which he petitioned that the
faithful workmen would receive it after the completion of the Temple), and to the
Volume of the Sacred Law (into which the key to its eventual recovery is placed,
and by the study of which it is later to be found by Joshua, Zerubbabel, and
Haggai.)

{{endnote candidate-names}}
Pronouncing Names of Candidates

While it may be tempting to replace the list of candidate's names with "several
Companions" as a matter of convenience, every effort should be made to actually
pronounce the name of each candidate as a mater of respect, and a sign of the
seriousness and solemnity of our rites, most especially upon their first introduction
to the Council. To facilitate this, it is best to furnish a written list of candidate
names to the I._M., C._G., and C._C. before the degree begins.

{{endnote cherubim}}
Cherub / Cherubim ___ [[rtl]]כְּרֻבִים[[/rtl]] / [[rtl]]כְּרוּבִים[[/rtl]] / [[rtl]]כְּרוּב[[/rtl]]

The Hebrew pronunciation is ker-oo-veem. There is no sound in Hebrew like the
"ch" in the English word "child," so the combination "ch" in transliterated words
always represents a soft "k" sound. As most Biblical names came into English
usage by way of their Latin spelling, the spelling distinction between /v/ and /b/
was not retained. This shift is apparent in names such as Avraham (Abraham) and
Rivkah (Rebecca.) Based upon the Latin spelling, therefore, the name of these
heavenly creatures can also be pronounced ker-oo-beem.

The singular form is Cherub (ker-oov), which is a masculine noun, and it is made
plural by addition of the -im suffix. There are a few places in the King James
Version of the Bible where the translators added an English plural suffix to the
already plural word, arriving at Cherubims. This unusual construction is not
retained in other Biblical translations, and is never used in the Cryptic Ritual.

%PAGE
{{endnote solomons-reading}}
Solomon's Scripture Reading

It may be desirable to produce a suitable scroll from which King Solomon may
recite the designated scriptural verses for the eight circumambulations, or to
provide him with a Bible in which these passages are marked.

It is anachronistic for King Solomon to be reciting from the Book of Revelation
during the seventh and eighth circuits, as it would not be composed for a over a
millenium after his death, nevertheless, the founders of our Order deemed the
symbolism of Revelation_22:12-14 to be significant to the Royal Master Degree,
and this is far from the only anachronism to be found in Masonic ritual.

{{endnote rm-obligation-placement}}
Placement of Several Candidates for Obligation

If there are more candidates than are able to kneel directly at the altar, any
remaining candidate(s) should be directed to stand behind those who are at the
altar, with their right hand over their heart, and their left hand upon the shoulder of
the Companion in front of them, so that every Candidate is linked to the Great
Lights upon the altar.

{{endnote rm-tools}}
Working Tools of a Royal Master

Many versions of this degree omit a description of the Working Tools, although
they may easily be found by observing the actions of its chief personage, Hiram
Abiff.

The symbolic inclusion of the tools here is particularly important, so as not to
detract from the unique quality held by the Most Excellent Master Degree (among
the Intermediate Degrees of the Capitular Rite), which is the only Degree with no
Working Tools, this fact being celebrated in song with the lyrics "There is no mor
occasion for Level or Plumbline, for Trowel or Gavel, for Compasses or Square;
our works are completed, the [[smallcaps]]ark[[/smallcaps]] safely seated, and we shall be greeted as
workmen most rare."

By contrast, H._A. here says, "My work, Companion Adoniram, is not complete,"
and it becomes the particular duty of the Companions and successors of H._A. to
complete this Work, a task that can only be accomplished thanks to plans drafted
by his skillful hands through use of the Pencil, the Compasses, and the Trestle- |
Board.

