{{endnote zabud}}
Zabud ___ [[rtl]]זָבוּד[[/rtl]]

The Hebrew pronunciation is zaw-vood, but as most Biblical names came into
English usage by way of their Latin spelling, the spelling distinction between /v/
and /b/ was not retained. This shift is apparent in names such as Avraham
(Abraham) and Rivkah (Rebecca.) Based upon the Latin spelling, therefore, this
name can also be pronounced zaw-bood. His name means bestowed or endowed.

He is referenced in the Biblical text only once, among the list of Solomon's
Princes and Officers in given in 1_Kings_4:1-21. These two lists are tabulated
here:

  1. Azariah, son of Zadok.
  2. Elihoreph, son of Shisha, a Scribe.
  3. Ahiah, son of Shisha, a Scribe.
  4. Jehoshaphat, son of Ahilud, the Recorder.
  5. Benaiah, son of Jehoiada, over the host (i.e., Captain of the Guard.)
  6. Zadok, a Priest.
  7. Abiathar, a Priest.
  8. Azariah, son of Nathan, chief over the tributary officers.
  9. [[strong]]Zabud[[/strong]], son of Nathan, principal officer, and the king's friend.
  10. [[strong]]Ahishar[[/strong]], chief of the household (i.e., the Steward)
  11. [[strong]]Adoniram[[/strong]], son of Abda, chief of the tribute ||
      (i.e., over the tributary officers.)
 
The Twelve Tributary Officers over all Israel:

  1. Ben-Hur, in mount Ephraim.
  2. Ben-Dekar, in Makaz, Shaalbim, Bethshemesh, and Elonbethhanan.
  3. Ben-Hesed, in Aruboth (with Sochoh and Hepher)
  4. Ben-Abinadab, in Dor; had the Daughter of Solomon to wife.
  5. Baana Ben-Ahilud (Taanach, Megiddo, Bethshean and its extents)
  6. Ben-Geber, in Ramothgilead (with Argob, sixty great cities)
  7. Ahinadab Ben-Iddo (Mahanaim)
  8. Ahimaaz, in Naphtali; took Basmath the Daughter of Solomon to wife.
  9. Baanah Ben-Hushai, in Asher and Aloth.
  10. Jehoshaphat Ben-Paruah, in Issachar.
  11. Shimei Ben-Elah, in Benjamin.
  12. Geber Ben-Uri, in the countries of Gilead, ||
      and of Sihon King of the Amorites, and of Og King of Bashan.

It is noteworthy that these lists combined contain 23 individuals, a number that,
along with the addition of the three Ancient Grand Masters, would be just one
member shy of the Council's "three times nine." The ritual of the Select Master
Degree, however, leads us in a different direction for the source of this number,
claiming that the S._V. was constructed by 22 men from Gebal, along with Ahishar,
Adoniram, and our Three Grand Master—a suggestion which includes some
notable overlap, but is not identical with this list. What is clear, however, is that
the job titles of the various Princes named in this passage were used as a source of
inspiration for the titles of the Officers of a Council, from whence we obtain a
Recorder, a Captain of the Guard, and a Steward, and also that Zabud's special
identification as a friend of King Solomon provided inspiration for the particular
narrative of the Select Master Degree.

{{endnote kneeling-prayer}}
Kneeling for the Benefit of Prayer

In Masonic Ritual of past eras, kneeling was commonly employed throughout the
work, but it has been found sensible to eliminate most kneeling to accommodate
those of our Brethren and Companions for whom, due to physical limitations and
advancing age, kneeling is impractical.

Because this portion of the ritual makes reference back to the language of the
Entered Apprentice Degree, however, where the candidate was first caused to
kneel, we have retained the instruction here. The stage directions, however, which
we have included, allow for a compromise, where those who remain standing may
place their right hand upon a Companion nearer to the altar, to suggest a symbolic
intention to kneel. Feel free to add an informal instruction such as "Those unable
to kneel may remain standing."

[[strong]]In the case that no Companion present is comfortable kneeling,[[/strong]] keep the
spoken ritual the same so that the reference to the EA° is still heard.

{{endnote sm-work-1-divine-pronouns}}
Capitalization of Divine Pronouns

See End Note for Page {{bookmark-page endnote-rm-divine-pronouns}} on this same topic.

{{endnote articles-for-deposit}}
Articles for Deposit within the Ninth Arch.

Within the Ninth Arch there should be one or more pedestals providing enough
space to accomodate the empty Substitute Ark with its lid open (either hinged, or
set to the side), together with a Scroll representing or containing the Book of the
Law, a representation of the Pot of Manna, a representation of Aaron's Rod
budded with blossoms and ripe almonds, a small piece of parchment #X, the
triangular plate, and three Ancient Master's Squares.

