{{endnote twenty-two}}
Twenty-two from Gebal, Ahishar, Adoniram...

%SPACING 0.22in
%LINE-HEIGHT 0.14in
[[em]]Hebrew pronunciations given in this entry are informational, but not required.
Further, the personal names of Solomon and Hiram, and the place names of
Lebanon and Tyre should always be pronunced in their familiar Anglicized form,
as used in the Craft Lodge.[[/em]]

%LINE-HEIGHT 0.15in
The Select Master Degree states that there could be no more than 27 men
employed in the erection of the Secret Vault: Twenty-two from Gebal, Ahishar
(Solomon's Grand Steward who is eventually replaced by Zabud), Adoniram, and
our Three Grand Masters:

%INDENT -0.2in
[[strong]]Gebal[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]גְבַל[[/rtl]] / ghev-al', or Latinized, gheb-al'), pronounced not with an initial J-
  sound, but with an unstressed-yet-hard G, was the Hebrew name of a city in
  Phoenicia, which is the same as modern day Byblos, Lebanon. In Arabic, the J
  sound is used, and in this tongue it is still known as Jbeil or Jubayl.

  {{cont}}Its ancient name means a twisted cord, border, boundary line, or limit, while its
  modern name, Byblos, comes from the Greek word for Papyrus. ||

  {{cont}}With the addition of the masculine plural suffix -im (-eem), Gebal can be
  rendered as [[strong]]Giblim[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]גִּבְלִים[[/rtl]] / ghib-leem), [[strong]]Gebalim[[/strong]] (ghev-a-leem), or further
  Anglicized as [[strong]]Gebalites[[/strong]] or [[strong]]Giblimites[[/strong]], all referring to the men of this city,
  which was under rule of the Phoenician King, Hiram of Tyre. Known for their
  craftsmanship, 1 Kings 5:18 says that "Gebalites" (which is simply translated as
  stone-squarers in the King James Version) prepared the stones for the Temple.
  As evidenced by this translation, their name has become synonymous with
  stone masons. The Brothers or Men of Tyre in a preceding degree, were known
  by names beginning with Jubel, which may share the same derivation as [[strong]]Gebal[[/strong]],
  thus the Faithful Giblimites and those wicked men of Tyre actually all hail from
  the same city.

[[strong]]Ahishar[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]אֲחִישָׁר[[/rtl]] / akh-ee-shawr'), the Steward of King Solomon's Household.
  His name is comprised of akh ([[rtl]]אָח[[/rtl]] / awkh) meaning "kin" which bears a first
  person possessive -iy suffix (becoming, "my kin"), together with the word shir
  ([[rtl]]שִׁיר[[/rtl]]) meaning "song"; or perhaps rather elided with the word yashar ([[rtl]]יָשָׁר[[/rtl]])
  meaning "upright."

  {{cont}}Taken together the name Ahishar means either "Brother of Song" or "my
  Brother is Upright." The latter possibility hints at the distinction in the
  performance of his duty which led to his demise in the legend of our Select
  Master Degree, after which his duties were [[strong]]bestowed[[/strong]] upon Zabud ([[rtl]]זָבוּד[[/rtl]] /
  zaw-vood') [[em]](See second End Note for Page {{bookmark-page endnote-zabud}}.)[[/em]]

[[strong]]Adoniram[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]אֲדֹנִירָם[[/rtl]] / ad-o-nee-rawm'), elsewhere called Adoram ([[rtl]]וַאֲדֹרָ֖ם[[/rtl]] / ad- <|
  o-rawm'), was the Son of Abda and King Solomon's chief officer over the
  Tribute (tax collection), meaning that he had oversight of the regional tributary
  officers. ([[em]]See second End Note for Page {{bookmark-page endnote-zabud}}.[[/em]])

  {{cont}}His name means "my Master has Exalted," although among Masons, it has
  sometimes been understood as Adonhiram ([[rtl]]חִירָם[[/rtl]]-[[rtl]]אָדוֹן[[/rtl]] / aw-don khee-rawm')
  "Master Hiram."

  {{cont}}He is mentioned in 1_Kings_4:6 and 5:14. The Royal Master Degree names him
  as the Fellowcraft who converses with Hiram Abiff, being given an indication
  as to where the [[smallcaps]]Word[[/smallcaps]] will be buried, but the Select Master Degree names
  him as Captain of the Guard during the construction of the Secret Vault. If this
  is indeed the same character, it indicates that he proved worthy of the trust
  imposed in him, and earned a promotion that allowed him to assist in carrying
  Hiram's plan into execution. His duties as a Tributary Officer would imply that
  one of his principal responsibilities was to Guard over the wealth accumulated
  by King Solomon, the foremost items of which would be those valuable Sacred
  Treasures deposited in the Secret Vault.

[[strong]]Solomon[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]שְׁלמֹה[[/rtl]] / shel-o-mo'), son of David, and second King of the United
  Kingdom of Israel & Judah. His name is derived from the word shalem ([[rtl]]שָׁלַם[[/rtl]] /
  shaw-lam') meaning complete, sound, or peaceful, and shares this root
  with the name of the city from which he ruled: Jerusalem ([[rtl]]יְרוּשָׁלַם[[/rtl]] /
  yer-oo-shaw-lah'-im.)

[[strong]]Hiram[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]חִירָם[[/rtl]] / khee-rawm') or ([[rtl]]חוּרָם[[/rtl]] / khoo-rawm') a name shared by the King
  of Tyre, and by an artificer of Temple artifacts mentioned in 2 Chronicles 4:16,
  [[strong]]Hiram Aviv[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]חִירָם אָבִיו[[/rtl]] / khee-rawm awh-veev) or [[strong]]Hiram Abiff[[/strong]]. Aviv
  (Abiff) translates literally to "his father."

%INDENT 0
In addition to the above personal names from among the 28 total men (including
Zabud) employed in the erection of the secret vault, and also to Gebal, the name of
the city of origin of the remaining twenty-two, a brief enumeration of the other
associated place names is also warranted:

%INDENT -0.2in
[[strong]]Lebanon[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]לְבָנוֹן[[/rtl]] / lev-aw-nohn') meaning "whiteness", is the mountainous region
  parallel to the Mediterranean coast which begins in Galilee and extends north
  for about 150 miles, having been named for its snow.

[[strong]]Tyre[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]צוֺר[[/rtl]] / [[rtl]]צֹר[[/rtl]] / tsore) meaning "a rock", a Phoenician coastal city, settled by
  the people of Sidon to establish a new harbor. It became the leading city of
  Phoenicia in 969 BCE under the reign of King Hiram I.

[[strong]]Sidon[[/strong]] ([[rtl]]צִידוֹן[[/rtl]] / tsee-done') a Phoenician city north of Tyre. Its name means
  "hunting", and is used in this case in the sense of catching fish.

[[strong]]Phoenicia[[/strong]] (Φοινίκη / foy-nee'-kay) is the term which eventually came to be used
  for the whole geographic coastal region of what is now modern Lebanon
  including adjoining parts of modern Syria and Israel. This region, notable for
  its merchants and importance in cross-border trade, is where the first alphabetic
  writing system came into existence. It was a Consonantal Alphabet (or "abjad")
  which is referred to today as Proto-Sinaitic or Proto-Canaanite, and eventually
  became the Phoenician alphabet (from whence we derive the English word
  Phonetic, meaning "representing sounds.") This alphabet in turn gave rise
  to Paleo-Hebrew and Greek. Curiously, the number of letters present in the
  Phoenician and Hebrew Alphabets is twenty-two, corresponding with the
  number of men from Gebal.
%INDENT 0

{{endnote sm-closing-usual}}
... an Ancient Number, and a Usual Number.

See End Note for Page {{bookmark endnote-ancient-usual}} on this same topic.

